[src:web-middleware/application-server] Mobile application servers provide data delivery to mobile devices.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] The **front controller** software design pattern is listed in several pattern catalogs and is related to the design of web applications.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] It is "a controller that handles all requests for a website," which is a useful structure for web application developers to achieve flexibility and reuse without code redundancy.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] Front controllers are often used in web applications to implement workflows.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] While not strictly required, it is much easier to control navigation across a set of related pages (for instance, multiple pages used in an online purchase) from a front controller than it is to assign individual pages responsibility for navigation.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] The front controller may be implemented as a Java object, or as a script in a scripting language such as PHP, Raku, Python or Ruby that is called for every request of a web session.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] This script would handle all tasks that are common to the application or the framework, such as session handling, caching and input filtering.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] Based on the specific request, it would then instantiate further objects and call methods to handle the required tasks.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] The alternative to a front controller is the usage of page controllers mapped to each site page or path.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] Although this may cause each individual controller to contain duplicate code, the page-controller approach delivers a high degree of specialization.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] Request processor: used for request processing and modifying or retrieving the appropriate model.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] Flow manager: determines what will be shown on the next page.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] There are three primary benefits associated with the front controller pattern.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] The front controller pattern may incur performance issues because the single controller is performing a great deal of work, and handlers may introduce bottlenecks if they involve database or document queries.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] The front controller approach is also more complex than that of page controllers.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] The data for the application is best handled in a single location, obviating the need for duplicate data-retrieval code.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] Different roles in the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern should be separated to increase testability, which is also true for the controller part in the MVC pattern.
[src:web-middleware/front-controller] The page-controller pattern is an alternative to the front controller approach in the MVC model.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware often enables interoperability between applications that run on different operating systems, by supplying services so the application can exchange data in a standards-based way.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware sits "in the middle" between application software that may be working on different operating systems.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] It is similar to the middle layer of a three-tier single system architecture, except that it is stretched across multiple systems or applications.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Examples include EAI software, telecommunications software, transaction monitors, and messaging-and-queueing software.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] The distinction between operating system and middleware functionality is, to some extent, arbitrary.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] While core kernel functionality can only be provided by the operating system itself, some functionality previously provided by separately sold middleware is now integrated in operating systems.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] A typical example is the TCP/IP stack for telecommunications, nowadays included virtually in every operating system.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware is defined as software that provides a link between separate software applications.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] It is sometimes referred to as plumbing because it connects two applications and passes data between them.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware allows data contained in one database to be accessed through another.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] This makes it particularly useful for enterprise application integration and data integration tasks.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] It also facilitated distributed processing, the connection of multiple applications to create a larger application, usually over a network.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] when compared to the operating system and network services.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware offers some unique technological advantages for business and industry.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] For example, traditional database systems are usually deployed in closed environments where users access the system only via a restricted network or intranet (e.g., an enterprise’s internal network).
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] With the phenomenal growth of the World Wide Web, users can access virtually any database for which they have proper access rights from anywhere in the world.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware addresses the problem of varying levels of interoperability among different database structures.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware facilitates transparent access to legacy database management systems (DBMSs) or applications via a web server without regard to database-specific characteristics.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Businesses frequently use middleware applications to link information from departmental databases, such as payroll, sales, and accounting, or databases housed in multiple geographic locations.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] In the highly competitive healthcare community, laboratories make extensive use of middleware applications for data mining, laboratory information system (LIS) backup, and to combine systems during hospital mergers.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware helps bridge the gap between separate LISs in a newly formed healthcare network following a hospital buyout.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware can help software developers avoid having to write application programming interfaces (API) for every control program, by serving as an independent programming interface for their applications.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] For Future Internet network operation through traffic monitoring in multi-domain scenarios, using mediator tools (middleware) is a powerful help since they allow operators, searchers and service providers to supervise Quality of service and analyse eventual failures in telecommunication services.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Finally, e-commerce uses middleware to assist in handling rapid and secure transactions over many different types of computer environments.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] In short, middleware has become a critical element across a broad range of industries, thanks to its ability to bring together resources across dissimilar networks or computing platforms.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] In 2004 members of the European Broadcasting Union (EBU) carried out a study of Middleware with respect to system integration in broadcast environments.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] This involved system design engineering experts from 10 major European broadcasters working over a 12-month period to understand the effect of predominantly software-based products to media production and broadcasting system design techniques.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] The resulting reports Tech 3300 and Tech 3300s were published and are freely available from the EBU web site.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Message-oriented middleware (MOM) is middleware where transactions or event notifications are delivered between disparate systems or components by way of messages, often via an enterprise messaging system.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] With MOM, messages sent to the client are collected and stored until they are acted upon, while the client continues with other processing.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] software may queue, duplicate, translate and deliver messages to disparate systems or components in a messaging system.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Intelligent Middleware (IMW) provides real-time intelligence and event management through intelligent agents.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] The IMW manages the real-time processing of high volume sensor signals and turns these signals into intelligent and actionable business information.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] The actionable information is then delivered in end-user power dashboards to individual users or is pushed to systems within or outside the enterprise.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] It is able to support various heterogeneous types of hardware and software and provides an API for interfacing with external systems.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] It should have a highly scalable, distributed architecture which embeds intelligence throughout the network to transform raw data systematically into actionable and relevant knowledge.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] It can also be packaged with tools to view and manage operations and build advanced network applications most effectively.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Content-centric middleware offers a simple *provider-consumer* abstraction through which applications can issue requests for uniquely identified content, without worrying about where or how it is obtained.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Juno is one example, which allows applications to generate content requests associated with high-level delivery requirements.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] The middleware then adapts the underlying delivery to access the content from sources that are best suited to matching the requirements.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] This is therefore similar to Publish/subscribe middleware, as well as the Content-centric networking paradigm.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware enables a client to use services running on remote systems.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware, it is possible for applications to send objects and request services in an object-oriented system.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] is middleware between applications and database servers.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] integration interface that operates between embedded applications, the embedded operating system, and external applications.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliance is a generic term referring to any form of middleware that manages policy rules.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] They can mediate between data owners or producers, data aggregators, and data users.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Among heterogeneous institutional systems or networks they may be used to enforce, reconcile, and monitor agreed information management policies and laws across systems (or between jurisdictions) with divergent information policies or needs.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliances support policy-based information management processes by enabling rules-based processing, selective disclosure, and accountability and oversight.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] IBM, Red Hat, Oracle Corporation and Microsoft are some of the vendors that provide middleware software.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Vendors such as Axway, SAP, TIBCO, Informatica, Objective Interface Systems, Pervasive, ScaleOut Software and webMethods were specifically founded to provide more niche middleware solutions.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Groups such as the Apache Software Foundation, OpenSAF, the ObjectWeb Consortium (now OW2) and OASIS' AMQP encourage the development of open source middleware.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Microsoft .NET "Framework" architecture is essentially "Middleware" with typical middleware functions distributed between the various products, with most inter-computer interaction by industry standards, open APIs or RAND software licence.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Solace provides middleware in purpose-built hardware for implementations that may experience scale.
[src:web-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] StormMQ provides Message Oriented Middleware as a service.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] The **reactor** software design pattern is an event handling strategy that can respond to many potential service requests concurrently.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] The pattern's key component is an event loop, running in a *single* thread or process, which demultiplexes incoming requests and dispatches them to the correct request handler.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] By relying on event-based mechanisms rather than blocking I/O or multi-threading, a reactor can handle many concurrent I/O bound requests with minimal delay.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] A reactor also allows for easily modifying or expanding specific request handler routines, though the pattern does have some drawbacks and limitations.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] With its balance of simplicity and scalability, the reactor has become a central architectural element in several server applications and software frameworks for networking.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] Derivations such as the **multireactor** and proactor also exist for special cases where even greater throughput, performance, or request complexity are necessary.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] Practical considerations for the client–server model in large networks, such as the C10k problem for web servers, were the original motivation for the reactor pattern.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] A naive approach to handle service requests from many potential endpoints, such as network sockets or file descriptors, is to listen for new requests from within an event loop, then immediately read the earliest request.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] Once the entire request has been read, it can be processed and forwarded on by directly calling the appropriate handler.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] An entirely "iterative" server like this, which handles one request from start-to-finish per iteration of the event loop, is logically valid.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] However, it will fall behind once it receives multiple requests in quick succession.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] The iterative approach cannot scale because reading the request blocks the server's only thread until the full request is received, and I/O operations are typically much slower than other computations.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] One strategy to overcome this limitation is multi-threading: by immediately splitting off each new request into its own worker thread, the first request will no longer block the event loop, which can immediately iterate and handle another request.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] This "thread per connection" design scales better than a purely iterative one, but it still contains multiple inefficiencies and will struggle past a point.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] From a standpoint of underlying system resources, each new thread or process imposes overhead costs in memory and processing time (due to context switching).
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] The fundamental inefficiency of each thread waiting for I/O to finish isn't resolved either.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] From a design standpoint, both approaches tightly couple the general demultiplexer with specific request handlers too, making the server code brittle and tedious to modify.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] Combining these insights leads to the reactor pattern, which balances the advantages of single-threading with high throughput and scalability.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] The reactor pattern can be a good starting point for any concurrent, event-handling problem.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] The pattern is not restricted to network sockets either; hardware I/O, file system or database access, inter-process communication, and even abstract message passing systems are all possible use-cases.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] However, the reactor pattern does have limitations, a major one being the use of callbacks, which make program analysis and debugging more difficult, a problem common to designs with inverted control.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] The simpler thread-per-connection and fully iterative approaches avoid this and can be valid solutions if scalability or high-throughput are not required.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] Single-threading can also become a drawback in use-cases that require maximum throughput, or when requests involve significant processing.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] Different multi-threaded designs can overcome these limitations, and in fact, some still use the reactor pattern as a sub-component for handling events and I/O.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] An identifier and interface to a specific request, with IO and data.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] This will often take the form of a socket, file descriptor, or similar mechanism, which should be provided by most modern operating systems.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] of a handle, then notify other subsystems of a relevant status change (typically an IO handle becoming "ready to read").
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] The actual event loop of the reactive application, this component maintains the registry of valid event handlers, then invokes the appropriate handler when an event is raised.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] Also known as a request handler, this is the specific logic for processing one type of service request.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] The reactor pattern suggests registering these dynamically with the dispatcher as callbacks for greater flexibility.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] use multi-threading but invokes a request handler within the same thread as the dispatcher.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] An abstract interface class, representing the general properties and methods of an event handler.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] Each specific handler must implement this interface while the dispatcher will operate on the event handlers through this interface.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] The standard reactor pattern is sufficient for many applications, but for particularly demanding ones, tweaks can provide even more power at the price of extra complexity.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] One basic modification is to invoke event handlers in their own threads for more concurrency.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] Running the handlers in a thread pool, rather than spinning up new threads as needed, will further simplify the multi-threading and minimize overhead.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] This makes the thread pool a natural complement to the reactor pattern in many use-cases.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] Another way to maximize throughput is to partly reintroduce the approach of the "thread per connection" server, with replicated dispatchers / event loops running concurrently.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] However, rather than the number of connections, one configures the dispatcher count to match the available CPU cores of the underlying hardware.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] Known as a multireactor, this variant ensures a dedicated server is fully using the hardware's processing power.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] Because the distinct threads are long-running event loops, the overhead of creating and destroying threads is limited to server startup and shutdown.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] With requests distributed across independent dispatchers, a multireactor also provides better availability and robustness; should an error occur and a single dispatcher fail, it will only interrupt requests allocated to that event loop.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] For particularly complex services, where synchronous and asynchronous demands must be combined, one other alternative is the proactor pattern.
[src:web-middleware/reactor-pattern] This pattern is more intricate than a reactor, with its own engineering details, but it still makes use of a reactor subcomponent to solve the problem of blocking IO.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:web-middleware/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
